  "prompt": "What does mah mean on mobile battery?",
  "response": "\"mAh\" stands for **milliampere-hour**, and it is a unit of measure used to indicate the **capacity of a battery**. Specifically, it tells you how much energy a battery can store and deliver over time. \n\nHere\u2019s what it means in the context of mobile batteries:\n\n- **Higher mAh**: A battery with a higher mAh rating generally means it has a larger capacity and can last longer on a single charge, assuming other factors like power consumption are the same.\n- **Lower mAh**: A battery with a lower mAh rating has a smaller capacity and may need to be recharged more frequently.\n\nFor example:\n- A 3000 mAh battery can theoretically supply 3000 milliamperes (3 amperes) of current for one hour, or 1500 milliamperes for two hours, and so on.\n\nHowever, actual battery life also depends on how the device uses power (screen brightness, app usage, processor efficiency, etc.). So, while mAh is a useful indicator of capacity, it\u2019s not the only factor determining battery life.",
